уку/linear-algebra/lokr-into-linear-laye.content:
Appendix: converting LoKr into sequence of linear layers
By the definition of Kronicker product for C \in \mathbb{R}^{u_p \times u_q} and D \in \mathbb{R}^{v_p \times v_q}:
\begin{flalign}
    C \otimes D &amp;= \begin{pmatrix}
    c_{11} &amp; c_{12} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q} \\
    c_{21} &amp; c_{22} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q} \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    c_{u_p1} &amp; c_{u_p2} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_pu_q}
\end{pmatrix} \otimes \begin{pmatrix}
    d_{11} &amp; d_{12} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{1v_q} \\
    d_{21} &amp; d_{22} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{2v_q} \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    d_{v_p1} &amp; d_{v_p2} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{v_pv_q}
\end{pmatrix} = &amp;\\
&amp;= \begin{pmatrix}
    c_{11}D &amp; c_{12}D &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}D \\
    c_{21}D &amp; c_{22}D &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}D \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    c_{u_p1}D &amp; c_{u_p2}D &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_pu_q}D
\end{pmatrix} = &amp;\\
&amp;= \begin{pmatrix}
    c_{11}d_{11} &amp; c_{11}d_{12} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{11}d_{1v_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{12}d_{1v_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{1v_q} \\
    c_{11}d_{21} &amp; c_{11}d_{22} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{11}d_{2v_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{12}d_{2v_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{2v_q} \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    c_{11}d_{v_p1} &amp; c_{11}d_{v_p2} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{11}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{12}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{12}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{1u_q}d_{v_pv_q} \\
    c_{21}d_{11} &amp; c_{21}d_{12} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{21}d_{1v_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{22}d_{1v_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{1v_q} \\
    c_{21}d_{21} &amp; c_{21}d_{22} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{21}d_{2v_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{22}d_{2v_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{2v_q} \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    c_{21}d_{v_p1} &amp; c_{21}d_{v_p2} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{21}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{22}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{22}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{2u_q}d_{v_pv_q} \\
    \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
    c_{u_p1}d_{v_p1} &amp; c_{u_p1}d_{v_p2} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_p1}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{u_p2}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_p2}d_{v_pv_q} &amp; c_{u_p2}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_pu_q}d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; c_{u_pu_q}d_{v_pv_q}
\end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
We will just consider the case of C \otimes D, and the case where D is further split into BA naturally follows from this.
As an input we get b \times t \times q, where b - batch size, t - number of tokens and q - embedding size
To simplify things, let us just consider a single token of a single batch:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \mathbf{x} = \begin{pmatrix}
        x_{1} \\
        x_{2} \\
        \vdots \\
        x_{q}
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
Let us see what is the result of just multiplying \mathbf{x} and C \otimes D:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; (C \otimes D) \mathbf{x} = \begin{pmatrix}
        c_{11}d_{11}x_{1} + c_{11}d_{12}x_{2} + \dots + c_{11}d_{1v_q}x_{v_q} + c_{12}d_{11}x_{v_q+1} + \dots + c_{1u_q}d_{1v_q}x_{q} \\
        c_{11}d_{21}x_{1} + c_{11}d_{22}x_{2} + \dots + c_{11}d_{2v_q}x_{v_q} + c_{12}d_{21}x_{v_q+1} + \dots + c_{1u_q}d_{2v_q}x_{q} \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{11}d_{v_p1}x_{1} + c_{11}d_{v_p2}x_{2} + \dots + c_{11}d_{v_pv_q}x_{v_q} + c_{12}d_{v_p1}x_{v_q+1} + \dots + c_{1u_q}d_{v_pv_q}x_{q} \\
        c_{21}d_{11}x_{1} + c_{21}d_{12}x_{2} + \dots + c_{21}d_{1v_q}x_{v_q} + c_{22}d_{11}x_{v_q+1} + \dots + c_{2u_q}d_{1v_q}x_{q} \\
        \vdots \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{u_p1}d_{v_p1}x_{1} + c_{u_p1}d_{v_p2}x_{2} + \dots + c_{u_p1}d_{v_pv_q}x_{v_q} + c_{u_p2}d_{v_p1}x_{v_q+1} + \dots + c_{u_pu_q}d_{v_pv_q}x_{q}
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
We can see that there is a pattern: in each line d index increments by one every time, and every v_q times the d index is reset. Therefore, the first v_q elements of \mathbf{x} are dotted with the whole row of D and multiplied by the first element of C, the next v_q elements of \mathbf{x} are dotted with the whole row of D and multiplied by an element from C. For example, the first v_q elements of the first row’s sum can be rewritten: c_{11} \cdot D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x}[1..q_v], the next v_q elements as c_{12} \cdot D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x}[v_{q+1}..2v_q]; the first v_q elements of the second row as c_{11}D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x}[1..v_q], the next v_q elements as c_{12}D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x}[v_{q+1}..2v_q], etc.
This means that we can rewrite the above expression as:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \begin{pmatrix}
        c_{11}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x}[1..v_q] + c_{12}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x}[v_{q+1}..2v_q] + \dots + c_{1u_q}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x}[((u_q-1)v_q+1)..u_qv_q] \\
        c_{11}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x}[1..v_q] + c_{12}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x}[v_{q+1}..2v_q] + \dots + c_{1u_q}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x}[((u_q-1)v_q+1)..u_qv_q] \\
        \vdots \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{u_p1}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x}[1..v_q] + c_{u_p2}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x}[v_{q+1}..2v_q] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x}[((u_q-1)v_q+1)..u_qv_q]
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
We tend to take some parts of \mathbf{x}, to be specific every v_q element at once. We will rewrite \mathbf{x} as a v_q \times u_q matrix:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \mathbf{x&#039;} = \begin{pmatrix}
        x_1 &amp; x_{v_q+1} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{(u_q-1)v_q+1} \\
        x_2 &amp; x_{v_q+2} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{(u_q-1)v_q+2} \\
        \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
        x_{v_q} &amp; x_{2v_q} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{u_qv_q}
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
Now we can rewrite that matrix as:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \begin{pmatrix}
        c_{11}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q}D[1][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        c_{11}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q}D[2][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        \vdots \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{u_p1}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{u_p2}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q}D[v_p][:]\ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q]
    \end{pmatrix} = \heartsuit
\end{flalign}
Now let us go from the other end and see, what D \mathbf{x&#039;} is:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; D \mathbf{x&#039;} = \begin{pmatrix}
        d_{11} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{1v_q} \\
        d_{21} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{2v_q} \\
        \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
        d_{v_p1} &amp; \dots &amp; d_{v_pv_q}
    \end{pmatrix}
    \begin{pmatrix}
        x_1 &amp; x_{v_q+1} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{(u_q-1)v_q+1} \\
        x_2 &amp; x_{v_q+2} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{(u_q-1)v_q+2} \\
        \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
        x_{v_q} &amp; x_{2v_q} &amp; \dots &amp; x_{u_qv_q}
    \end{pmatrix} = &amp;\\
    &amp; = \begin{pmatrix}
        D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] &amp; D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] &amp; \dots &amp; D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] &amp; D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] &amp; \dots &amp; D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
        D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] &amp; D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] &amp; \dots &amp; D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q]
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; (D \mathbf{x&#039;})^T = \begin{pmatrix}
        D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] &amp; D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] &amp; \dots &amp; D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] \\
        D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] &amp; D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] &amp; \dots &amp; D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] \\
        \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots &amp; \vdots \\
        D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; \dots &amp; D[v_p][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q]
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; C (D \mathbf{x&#039;})^T = \begin{pmatrix}
        c_{11} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; c_{11} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; \dots\\
        c_{21} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{22} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{2u_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; c_{21} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{22} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{2u_q} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; \dots\\
        \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp; \ddots\\
        c_{u_p1} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{u_p2} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; c_{u_p1} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{u_p2} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] &amp; \dots
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
Now, if we concatinate the second row to the first, the third to them, etc… (flatten the matrix), we will get:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \begin{pmatrix}
        c_{11} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        c_{11} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{12} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{1u_q} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{21} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{22} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{2u_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        \vdots \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{u_p1} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{u_p2} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q} D[1][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
        \vdots \\
        c_{u_p1} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][1] + c_{u_p2} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][2] + \dots + c_{u_pu_q} D[2][:] \ \mathbf{x&#039;}[:][u_q] \\
    \end{pmatrix}
\end{flalign}
We can see that this is the same as \heartsuit.
If we denote turning \mathbf{x} into \mathbf{x&#039;} as reshape(\mathbf{x}), and flattening of the matrix as flatten(\mathbf{M}), we can write the above as:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \heartsuit = flatten(C \cdot (D \cdot reshape(\mathbf{x}))^T)
\end{flalign}

уку/pns/pns-sem-11.content:
Theoretical part
a
X_1, X_2, ... - i.i.d. r.v.’s with p.d.f \displaystyle f(x | \theta) = c \cdot e^{-\frac{x^2}{\theta}}
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} f(x | \theta) dx = c \cdot \int_{-\infty}^{+\infty} e^{-\frac{x^2}{\theta}}dx = c \cdot \sqrt{\pi \theta} = 1 \Rightarrow &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; c = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi \theta}} \text{ if } \theta &gt; 0 &amp;&amp;\\
\end{flalign}
So, \displaystyle f(x | \theta) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi \theta}} \cdot e^{-\frac{x^2}{\theta}}
Which means that \sqrt{\theta} = \sigma \sqrt{2},\ \theta = \sigma^2 \cdot 2 = 2 \sigma^2
b
moment method estimator \hat{\Theta} of \theta - ?
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \hat{\Theta} = 2 \cdot \frac{1}{n-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n}\lt(X_i - \overline{X}\rt)^2 = &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; 2 \frac{n}{n - 1} \lt(\widehat{m}_2 - \widehat{m}_1\zs^2\rt)
\end{flalign}
Alternatively, we can use the known \mu = 0:
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \hat{\Theta} = 2 \cdot \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(X_i-0)^2 = 2 \widehat{m}_2 &amp;&amp;\\
\end{flalign}
с
maximum likelihood estimator \hat{\Theta} of \theta - ?
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; \widetilde{\Theta} = \mathrm{argmax}_{\theta \in \Theta} \mathrm{lik} (\theta)&amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \mathrm{lik} = \prod_{k} f(X_k \mid \theta) = \prod_{k} \frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi \theta}} \cdot e^{-\frac{X_k^2}{\theta}} =\\
    &amp; = \lt(\frac{1}{\sqrt{\pi \theta}}\rt)^n \cdot e^{-\frac{1}{\theta} \sum_{k} X_k^2} &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \ln \mathrm{lik} = -n \ln \sqrt{\pi \theta} - \frac{1}{\theta} \sum_{k} X_k^2 &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \frac{d \ln \mathrm{lik}}{d \theta} = -\frac{n}{2 \theta} + \frac{1}{\theta^2} \sum_{k} X_k^2 = 0 &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; -n \theta + 2 \sum_{k} X_k^2 = 0 &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \widetilde{\Theta} = \frac{2}{n} \sum_{k} X_k^2 &amp;&amp;\\
\end{flalign}
d
Is \hat{\Theta} unbiased estimator of \theta?
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; E(\hat{\Theta}) = E\lt(2 \widehat{m}_2\rt) = 2 E(\widehat{m}_2) = 2 \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} E(X_i^2 - \mu) = &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \cmm{\Sigma X \sim \Gamma \lt(\frac{n}{2}, \frac{1}{\Theta}\rt)}{=}\ 2 \frac{1}{n} \cdot \frac{n}{2 \cdot \frac{1}{\theta}}
    = \theta \Rightarrow \hat{\Theta} \text{ is unbiased} \Rightarrow\\
    &amp; \Rightarrow \text{asymptotically unbiased} &amp;&amp;\\
\end{flalign}
e
MSE of \hat{\Theta} - ?
\begin{flalign}
    &amp; E \lt((\hat \Theta - \theta)^2\rt) = \lt( E(\hat \Theta) - \theta \rt)^2 + \mathrm{Var} (\hat \Theta) = &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; \cm{unbiased}{=} 0 + \mathrm{Var} (\hat \Theta) = \mathrm{Var} \lt(2 \widehat{m}_2\rt) = 4 \mathrm{Var} \lt(\widehat{m}_2\rt) = &amp;&amp;\\
    &amp; = 4 \mathrm{Var} \lt( \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^{n} X_i^2 \rt) = 4 \cdot \frac{1}{n^2} \cdot n \cdot \mathrm{Var} (X_i^2) = &amp;&amp;\\
\end{flalign}
= \frac{4}{n} \mathrm{Var} (X_i^2) = \frac{4}{n} \cdot 2 \cdot \frac{\theta^2}{4} = \heartsuit (math.stackexchange.com/questions/620045/mean-and-variance-of-squared-gaussian-y-x2-where-x-sim-mathcaln0-sigma)
\displaystyle \heartsuit = \frac{2 \theta^2}{n}
f
Is \hat{\Theta} consistent estimator of \theta?
(e): \displaystyle \mathrm{Var}(\widehat{\Theta}) = \frac{2 \theta^2}{n} \overset{n \to \infty}{\to}0\ \  - \heartsuit
\cm{asymptotically unbiased}{(d)} \land \heartsuit \cmu{Sufficient condition for consistency}{\Rightarrow} \hat{\Theta} is consistent

